qx|I1,Basic Structure|ht|b|fp|1|cs|1|cp|4|at|^-{  Basic Structure }
^-|ht|c|FP||cs||cp||AT|^B@2^*BMM: ^*NInverted Minor Raises are devised to make sure the partnership avoids bidding a doomed NT contract while they could make a simple partscore, or even game, in one of the minors. To start with let us quote from Susan Doty's web site. Fortunately, I have a saved copy from the site before it went down.|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

"After partner opens the bidding with 1@C or 1@D, responder will usually either have a 4 card major suit to show, or a balanced hand suitable for a NT response. Sometimes, though, responder cannot bid either and is forced to  support opener's minor. Playing standard responses, responder can make |
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

a single raise to 2 of the bid minor (showing 6-9 points) or an invitational raise to 3 of the bid minor (showing 10-12). Responder does not have a way to make a forcing raise with a stronger hand. This is one of the situations that Inverted Minor Raises were designed to deal with. Using ^*B"The Inverted Minor Raises", all you have to do is reverse the meaning of the two and the three  responses--thus inverted.^*N|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

The basic structure of Inverted Minor Raises is:
^B@2^*BSingle Raise: 1@C/2@C - 1@D/2@D:
Invitational or better values (10+ HCP); 4 card support (preferably 5); No 4 card major; Not suited for a direct 2NT (10-12 balanced) or 3NT (13-15 balanced) responses. 
Note: this bid is forcing for one round.

^B@2^*BJump Raise: 1@C/3@C - 1@D/3@D:
Preemptive (no more than 7 HCP)--About 6 to 9 support points (HCP + Dummy Points); 5+ card support ;  and no 4+card major.
With 8-9 HCP we have too many values to raise preemptively, so bid 1NT instead."  |
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|

- Both the single raise and jump raise must be alerted. 
- The single raise is off after interference. However, the Jump raise is not affected.
- Most expert play Inverted Minor Raises after a passed hand,|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|

A summary by Howard Schutzman is next.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


NT||
%%5Howard
HT|b|CS|1|CP|4|FP|1|at|^-{   How I play Inverted Minor Raises - by Howard   }
^-|CP||fp||at|
^B@21) If I make a minor raise (to either the 2 level or 3 level), I am guaranteed to have no 4-card major. |
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

2) I make a jump raise (to the 3 level) with 5 to a bad 9 points and a 5+ card suit. I might have the other minor, but feel that the jump raise is tactically the right thing to do to make it difficult for the opponents. I will tend to prefer the jump raise to a bid of 1N if I have 5-card support.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT| 

3) I make a limit raise with 10+ points and usually 5-card support. (The only time I will have 4-card support is if I am 4-4 in the minors and partner opens 1@D.) If partner opens clubs, I will not have 4 diamonds. If partner opens diamonds, I will not have 5+ clubs (in SAYC; in 2 over 1,  1@D/2@C is slightly more complicated).|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT| 

4) Opener should now respond with his lowest stopper. If responder has less than a game-forcing hand, he should continue to bid stoppers below three of the agreed upon suit, or 2N if he has ^*Iall the other suits stopped^*N. |
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT|

5) If responder has a game-forcing hand, he must make sure the partnership bids game by either bidding 3N, if all suits are stopped, or continue bidding new suits, if not. Again, new suits are forcing.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

6) Similarly, if opener has 15+ points, it is his responsibility to make sure the partnership reaches game by either bidding 3N, if all suits are stopped, or continuing to bid new suits, if not. |
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|

7) Once 3 suits have been bid (the original suit and 2 stopper suits), if someone bids the fourth suit, that is asking about a stopper rather than telling, because if the bidder has the remaining suit stopped, he can bid NT himself. |FP||
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


AT|

8) Inverted minors are off in competition (including over takeout doubles), in the sense that a raise to 2 is less than a limit raise. A raise to 3 is still preemptive.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


at|

Next step let us look at a few examples. In all you are sitting South and your partner opens one of the minors. |
