qx|I2, Full and Half-Stoppers|ht|b|fp|1|cs|1|cp|4|at|^-{  Stoppers }
^-|ht|c|FP||cs||cp||AT|^B@2^*BMM: ^*NIn Notrump, often, declarer needs to give up the lead to establish one or two other suits. He needs protection in his short suits to prevent the opponents running those suits. Those protections are ^*Bstoppers^*N. They are protected honor in 2+-card combinations. A short suit then may have none, a half, one, or more stopper. ^*BOne half-stopper (in the dummy) combined with another (in hand) will give the declarer one full stopper.^*N|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


AT|

All ^*Bunprotected singleton honors excluding the ace^*N and ^*Bxxx ^*N(3 small cards in short suits) have no stoppers.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


AT|

All the following holdings have two stoppers:
^*BA K
K Q J
Q J T 9
A Q x ^*N(If the K is under the suit, there are two stoppers; if the K is over it, there is only one).|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


AT|

All the following holdings have one stopper:
^*BA
K Q
Q J T
J 10 x x
K J x x ^*N(If the A and Q are under it, both the K and the J can stop the suit, however, if both the A and Q are over it, the K and the J are useless). ^*BK^*Nx has a particular position. It is a full stopper on opening lead if Kx is in declarer's hand (because if the suit is led, it is guaranteed to win a trick). But it is an iffy stopper if it is in dummy.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


AT|
 
The following suit contains a half stopper only:
^*BQ x x
Q x 
J x x x
J 10 x ^*N|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


